	<h1 style="text-indent:200px;"2>Harar Jugol Wall history</h1>
	<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 150%;padding-left: 33px;text-align:45%;line-height: 33px;">
		The Harar Jugol Wall is believed to have been built between the 13th and 16th centuries. The Harar Jugol Wall originally had five historic gates providing five entries into five different districts of the city. The wall was built as a defense in medieval times, an imposing 5m high and 3.5km long.&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp<a href="#aksum">Click Here To Read More About The Monument Of Aksum</a><br> The old town is surrounded by this fascinating wall with the famous gates, Shoa Gate, Buda Gate, Erer Gate, Sanga Gate and Fallana Gate. In 1889 a sixth gate, Harar gate, was added by Ras Makonnen, the first duke of Harar.<br>
The African and Islamic traditions influenced over a long period of time the development of the city and its typical urban planning and contributed to its particular character and uniqueness.<br> The present urban layout follows the 16th century design for an Islamic town with its central core occupied with commercial and religious buildings and a maze of narrow alleyways with imposing facades.

	</p>
	<img src="image/h2.jpg"width="70%"height="31%"align="center"style="padding-left: 17%;"><br>
	<a href="gonder.php"style="font-size: 150%;">The Castle Of Fasiledes</a><br>
		<a href="lal.php"style="font-size: 150%;">The Rock Hewn Church of Lalibela</a><br>
	<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 150%;padding-left: 33px;text-align:45%;line-height: 33px;">
		Modern Harar surrounds the old capital, which is Ethiopia’s only walled city. The ancient walls enclose a crowded Muslim town with alleyways that wind to a central marketplace. Outside the walls, the city spreads across the plateau and is characterized by northern Ethiopian and European architecture.<br> Because of ritual differences in slaughtering, separate Muslim and Christian marketplaces are maintained.
The city of Harar is located on a hilltop in the eastern extension of the Ethiopian Highlands, about five hundred kilometers from the capital Addis Ababa.&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp<a href="#aksum">Click Here To Read More About The Monument Of Aksum</a><br> The population includes the local Harari (Adere), who speak a Semitic language and have literature written in Arabic script, as well as the Amhara, Oromo, and Somalis.... 
The city of Harar is located on a hilltop in the eastern extension of the Ethiopian Highlands, about five hundred kilometers from the capital Addis Ababa.<br> The population includes the local Harari (Adere), who speak a Semitic language and have literature written in Arabic script, as well as the Amhara, Oromo, and Somalis..

	</p>
	<h1 style="background-color: #65A6A8;text-indent:200px;">What are the 5 gates of Jugol?</h1>
	<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 150%;padding-left: 33px;text-align:45%;line-height: 33px;">
		This fascinating wall once had five gates:
           <ol style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 150%;padding-left: 33px;text-align:45%;line-height: 33px;">
           	<li>Shoa Gate</li>
           	<li>Buda Gate</li>
           	<li>Sanga Gate</li>
           	<li>Erer Gate</li>
           	<li>Fallana Gate</li>
           </ol>
		<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 150%;padding-left: 33px;text-align:45%;line-height: 33px;"> and  each providing five pathways into five different quarters of the city. Still intact, the Jugol wall has become an icon of the city</div>
	</p>
	<h1 style="background-color:lightblue;text-indent:200px;">Why was Harar Jugol built?</h1>
	<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 150%;padding-left: 33px;text-align:45%;line-height: 33px;">
		Most notably, Harar city is known for its Jugol wall and the walled gates that are believed to be built somewhere between the 13th and 16th century. This thick, 5 m high and 3.5 km long Jugol wall was built as a defensive response to the people of the city in the medieval times.&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp<a href="#aksum">Click Here To Read More About The Monument Of Aksum</a>
	</p>
	<h1 style="background-color:lightskyblue;text-indent:200px;">Who built Harar Jugol?</h1>
	<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 150%;padding-left: 33px;text-align:45%;line-height: 33px;">
		The Islamic Arabic cleric Abadir Umar ar-Rida settled in Harar, located on a plateau surrounded by deep gorges and savannah, around 1216 AD. The historic Harar Jugol Walls were built during the 13th and 16th centuries, fortifying the town.
	</p>
